Now let me read the round-3 review and incorporation artifacts to understand what was incorporated.

I've read the aggregate spec, both child specs, the round-3 incorporation record, the relevant ADRs (007-010), and cross-checked the round-3 fixes against the schema, lifecycle, and migration plan. Two load-bearing gaps remain.

```json
{
  "blockers": [
    {
      "id": "B-001",
      "section": "_techspec_orchestration.md §Data Models / `task_runs` continuation columns + _techspec_review_gate.md §Data Model / `task_runs` Review Trigger and Continuation Columns + Aggregate Implementation Steps (#9)",
      "issue": "The continuation columns on `task_runs` have a forward foreign key `review_id TEXT NULL REFERENCES task_run_reviews(review_id)` and `parent_run_id TEXT NULL REFERENCES task_runs(id)`, but two specs claim ownership of the migration. The orchestration child says 'Add the review trigger and continuation columns in the same task-run migration family' (i.e. orchestration step 1), while the aggregate Implementation Step 9 says review-gate migrations 'include continuation columns on `task_runs`'. Worse, `task_run_reviews` is created in the review-gate migration (step 9), so if orchestration step 1 declares the FK to `task_run_reviews(review_id)` the schema is unloadable until step 9, and SQLite cannot retro-add the FK without table-rewrite. Implementers will have to invent ordering, drop the FK, or duplicate migrations.",
      "rationale": "Grenfield/hard-cuts rule says renames/migrations land in a single coordinated change; ADR-002/ADR-009 require typed continuation state with explicit FKs. Two child specs declaring conflicting ownership of the same migration violates the 'aggregate is authoritative for sequencing' precedence (Aggregate §Normative Sources and Precedence). This is exactly the schema-without-migration / partial-surface-completion class flaged in the review charter.",
      "suggested_fix": "Pin migration ownership in one place: either (a) make the review-gate migration create `task_run_reviews` and the `task_runs` continuation columns + FKs in one numbered migration (and remove the columns from `_techspec_orchestration.md`'s data model), or (b) split the task_runs continuation columns into a third migration that runs after both, with a single typed home. Then update Aggregate §Implementation Steps and the Build Order in `_techspec_orchestration.md` so step ordering matches FK ordering. Restate the chosen ownership in ADR-009."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-002",
      "section": "_techspec_orchestration.md §Integration Points / Bridge terminal task notifier flow + §Hook dispatch mapping (`notification.terminal_state_mismatch`)",
      "issue": "The bridge terminal notifier filters candidate events on run-level terminals (`task.run_completed`, `task.run_failed`, `task.run_canceled`) plus `task.canceled`, then 'reloads current task state ... and verifies the task is actually terminal'. The N-010 fix mandates fail-closed (no delivery, no cursor advance, `notification.terminal_state_mismatch`) when the replayed terminal event and current task state disagree. But under review-gate continuation, a run is terminally `completed/failed/canceled` while the task is still mid-review (not yet task-terminal). That is exactly the 'disagreement' case under the current rules, so every review-rejected task will permanently stall the bridge cursor and emit a false `terminal_state_mismatch` alarm. The two MVP tracks contradict each other on the happy path.",
      "rationale": "Aggregate §End-to-End Lifecycle explicitly carries the bridge notifier through the review-rejected continuation path, and the Test Strategy demands a real-scenario QA covering 'reviewer rejecting incomplete work, a continuation worker applying missing_work, reviewer approval, and bridge terminal notification delivery'. As written, that QA cannot pass: the cursor is fail-closed before the continuation worker even starts. This is hidden coupling to the review-gate state machine and a partial-surface failure for the orchestration child.",
      "suggested_fix": "Either (a) change the notifier candidate filter to fire only on the task-terminal event (introduce/repurpose a single `task.terminal` event written by `task.Service` after review acceptance, and stop filtering run-level terminals), or (b) split the recheck into three states in `_techspec_orchestration.md`: terminal+match → deliver+advance; non-terminal task with review pending → skip without delivery and without advance, retry on next wake (no `terminal_state_mismatch`); terminal disagreement → fail-closed alarm as today. Update the Test Strategy to cover the review-rejected continuation cursor invariant explicitly, and update ADR-003/ADR-007 cross-references so the review-gate lifecycle and notifier filter share one truth."
    }
  ],
  "nits": [
    {
      "id": "N-001",
      "section": "_techspec_review_gate.md §Reviewer Routing / `ReviewerSelector` + §Review Policy / `ReviewProfile`",
      "issue": "`ReviewProfile` and `ReviewerSelector` both declare `AgentName`, `Provider`, `Model`, `AllowedAgentNames`, `PreferredAgentNames` with no precedence rule, leaving 'effective selector' computation ambiguous for implementers and tests.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add a one-paragraph precedence rule (or a small mapping table) stating that `ReviewProfile` scalars seed the effective `ReviewerSelector` unless the selector explicitly overrides them; pin this in ADR-010."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-002",
      "section": "_techspec_review_gate.md §Lifecycle / Review-request transaction boundary",
      "issue": "Spec specifies seting `review_required=1` on terminal commit and using it for crash recovery, but never specifies when/where `review_required` is cleared after a successful follow-up review-request creation; recovery loop is at risk of repeated re-request attempts.",
      "suggested_fix": "State explicitly that the follow-up review-request transaction clears `task_runs.review_required` (and writes the review_id back) in the same transaction that inserts the `task_run_reviews` row."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-003",
      "section": "_techspec_review_gate.md §Failure Policy + §Data Model / `task_run_reviews.attempt`",
      "issue": "Reviewer attempt retry semantics for `error|timeout|invalid_output` are not pinned: unclear whether a retry inserts a new `task_run_reviews` row with `attempt+1` or updates the existing row, and whether the unique `(reviewer_session_id) WHERE status IN ('routed','in_review')` index is honored across retries.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add one paragraph stating that each retry inserts a new attempt row, and that the prior attempt's status moves to a terminal attempt status before a new binding is opened, so the partial unique index is never violated."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-004",
      "section": "_techspec_review_gate.md §Reviewer Routing / Eligibility rules — original-worker exclusion",
      "issue": "Original-worker exclusion compares 'session id, agent name, peer id, and actor identity against the reviewed run's terminalizing session/agent/peer metadata', but the orchestration data model never names the specific `task_runs` columns that store this terminalizing metadata, so the comparison is implementation-defined.",
      "suggested_fix": "Enumerate the source columns (e.g. `task_runs.claimed_by_session_id`, `claimed_by_agent_name`, `claimed_by_peer_id`, `terminalized_by_*`) in `_techspec_orchestration.md` data model so the eligibility check is testable."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-005",
      "section": "_techspec_review_gate.md §Native Tool Contract / Tool authorization",
      "issue": "'Operator/debug contexts with permission' for `submit_run_review` is under-specified; without a named permission/actor class, implementers may invent a backdoor that breaks the reviewer-binding invariant.",
      "suggested_fix": "Either delete that escape hatch from MVP or pin it to a specific operator role/permission already enforced in `internal/api/core` and add a boundary test that proves session actors without a binding cannot use the operator path."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-006",
      "section": "_techspec_review_gate.md §Data Model / `task_run_reviews` indexes",
      "issue": "Idempotent `(run_id, review_round)` request creation has no SQL-level uniqueness; it relies on app-level checks inside `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`. With the multi-attempt model this is fine in single-process daemon, but the invariant is implicit.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add a partial unique index on `(run_id, review_round) WHERE status = 'requested'` (or document why one cannot exist) so the idempotency claim is enforced at the storage layer."
    }
  ],
  "readiness": "NEEDS_REWORK",
  "summary": "Round-3 closed the six load-bearing gaps (continuation columns, reviewer-session binding, ReviewRouter wake, RecordRunReview atomicity, ParticipantPolicy enforcement, follow-up request transaction) cleanly, but the act of adding those columns surfaced two new blockers: the migration plan double-claims ownership of the `task_runs` continuation columns and creates an FK ordering hazard against `task_run_reviews`, and the bridge terminal notifier's fail-closed rule contradicts the review-rejected continuation path on the documented happy path. Both must be reconciled before task generation; the remaining items are non-blocking clarifications."
}
```
